How SQL Server Audit Logs Who Queried a Table

SQL Server Audit is a built-in feature that records who accessed sensitive data, when, and how.

We define an Audit that captures activity (for example, SELECT queries on phi_data).

When anyone runs a query, SQL Server automatically logs:

User/Login who executed it

Time of execution

Action taken (e.g., SELECT, UPDATE)

Object queried (table or view name)

The log is stored in a secure audit file (or Windows log), outside the normal database, so it cannot be altered by the user.

